snippet.textDisplay:
Warning: This is a very long post, but I think you guys @Corridor will enjoy it. Read it on a coffee break. Maybe read it in brief snippets, about one video at a time. If you want to TLDR, open the 3rd and 4th links and read the stuff I’ve written around them. If you can, please don’t skim the article. Anyway..


I am a fan of people using extremely limited tools to do great work or sometimes even borderline competent work. So I’m gonna give you some examples of legacy VFX, in some cases just rigging/stunt-work that I thought looked cool, and finally come somewhere near modern digital.


The first one. Roger Rabbit-style integration of animation and real characters. Song from “Raja Chinna Roja” (1989).
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WhKuKiTej9A


Other than the movement of the animated characters - they seem to slide a little, I’m amazed it is as good as it is. We didn’t have animated movies in the 80’s. Or TV shows. Only imported ones. Where did they get the people to do this? How much training and experience did they even have?




“Star Wars” song from “Anjali” 1990. DISCLAIMER: I’ll explain more, but this song has TONS of very literal Star Wars references. And nobody should care about a 30 year old movie but Disney/Star Wars copyright people are weird. Maybe don’t feature this on the channel. But I just wanted to share it with you guys, and perhaps the community here because this song is so weird and makes me nostalgic.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DERJ4ml8rDY


So the context is - this is a movie about an “impaired” child (I don’t remember in what way) and how her parents, brother etc deal with it. In this scene they are reading them a storybook at night and as children’s books do it has horrifying imagery which triggers a shared nightmare sequence, which basically becomes an excuse for the director to put in as many references to pop-culture influences of the past decade as he could. (The song is literally called Star Wars, and has a mild callout to Indiana Jones face-melting, and ET!)


Unfortunately motion-tracking is really bad in this. There is no story I can follow. Which is ironic considering the director Mani Ratnam is practically a legend known for the emotional depth of his stories, technical competence, and the movie itself won 3 National Awards. (which in terms of respectability and legitimacy were right up there with the Oscars.)


But, REFERENCES! Lots of very literal props! It’s sort of fun, in a weird way.




Moving to 1993! A song from the movie Gentleman, directed by Shankar (yes the same guy who made Enthiran, or “Indian Terminator” as you so gaspably awfully called it a few episodes ago). He has basically been a lonely visual effects and special effects evangelist and pioneer in Indian cinema, trying some new effect or vfx trick in every movie of his, even if in the 90’s it was mostly for fun rather than impact (until the tools got a lot better in this century and he went full-throttle on the fx with Enthiran).
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mmYoBNtWEqI


Jump to 0:36 for the effects, they last about 20 seconds. Again, traditional animation. Well integrated, and done with presumably a limited talent pool.


Mukkala Mukkabla song from Kadhalan, 1994. And the movie was made by - you guessed it - Shankar.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PjT12Ce0Kw8


Jump to 4:16 for the visual effects. But I encourage you to watch the whole song, it’s so goofy and fun. Here is another one from the same movie; there are no vfx shots in this one, but I kinda wanted to give an idea of the goofy/fun tone that the choreographer Prabhudeva (the guy dancing) almost always goes for:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5vkRRYMlmuo


Onto 1998: A song from the movie Jeans, again by Shankar. Basically, a girl is pretending to be twins and “they” are forced to do a dance performance together for the whole family’s and in-law’s entertainment. So the girl’s brother helps her by setting up a holographic projection as her twin, with him putting on a mo-cap suit to provide the motion for the hologram. Yes, everything I said is exactly what happens in the movie, I’m not drunk.


The song alone is at this link:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HnW2737FkW8


There is a longer version with an “explainer” scene (and other fluff) here:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6roRB7SlJPs


In the shorter version, the “hologram” part starts at 1:18. Basically most of the song after this is about the double/twin thing, with an interesting hand-locking at 2:28. Things in the scene go wrong at 2:53, the hologram collapses at 3:54 and the first 3D models show up at 4:26. The part I love is at 4:50, where everything has gone to hell and the said 3D model finishes off the performance a set of classical dance moves with absolute grace and formality. :)


YouTube overlays ruin the part at 4:50 a bit, so jump to the “explainer” link I provided and go to 5:03.




Shankar has done a lot more fx work in his movies between Jeans (1998) and Enthiran (2013). But these are the ones I thought were most interesting. There is also one other director I want to talk about but this post is already an essay.


A few more random things:


1) This entire list is songs. Yes, we spend more on songs than anything else in the movie.


2) This is something I don’t think you mentioned. But most of the movie Enthiran was actually driven by legacy effects, rather than vfx (until the climactic fight scenes that is). There are several scenes where the “scientists” are working with robot prototypes and in those scenes, Stan Winston Studio did the animatronics. Although they are a tiny bit jankier than I thought they would be.




3) I just love the over-the-top explosions in this one. (Mudhalvan 1999, again by director Shankar):
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3E5d3bAG5Dw


Jump to 1:18 to skip dialog and some useless shooting/people-falling. Summary: Trees get blown up, cows traumatised, carts get upset. Very upset. It’s 1999 so I’m guessing the trees are digital.

snippet.textDisplay:
Have any of you seen RWBY? It is an anime style show that is fully CGI. It was also made by an extremely small team. It has a very distinctive look because of this. It would be very interesting to see you guys break down why exactly it looks the way it does, like what features seem to be in use and what don't.



On a related note: Netflix's version of the anime Baki has some absolutely stellar fight sequences. A few of those feature some clearly computer generated portions. There's a weight and a feel to the movement of the characters as they fight that just isn't there in the other scenes. It leaves the art style and flow a bit disjointed, although the fight scenes are still superb. Hard to describe, but you'll know it when you see it. I'd be interested to know how you get a three-D model or whatever they're using to look properly hand drawn, because Baki clearly doesn't quite hit the mark. I'd also like to know why one might choose to use that when they're already doing old fashion animation for the other parts.

Part one Episode nine is the best example of this computer generated anime fight technique. Also, just as a small warning Baki is extraordinarily violent.
